The Cascade. It represents about 80% of the true exam reality.

🚨 Pre-Flight Setup
Environment: RHEL 9 VM (Do not use RHEL 10 for this).

Hardware: Add ONE unformatted 10GB virtual disk (/dev/vdb).

Network: Ensure the VM has an active internet connection to pull container images and packages.

Time Limit: 150 Minutes (2.5 hours).

The Golden Rule: You must reboot at the end. If it doesn't survive a reboot, you score 0 for that objective.

📝 RHCSA Mock Exam Level 3: "The Cascade"
Task 1: The Foundation (Storage)
Your company requires a dedicated storage pool for a new application.

Create a Volume Group named app_vg using your 10GB disk, with a physical extent size of 32MB.

Create a Logical Volume named lv_webdata that uses exactly 50 extents.

Format the volume with the xfs filesystem.

Mount it persistently to /srv/web_content.

Task 2: The Identity Matrix (Users & Groups)
The development team needs access to the new storage.

Create a group named web_devs.

Create two users: natasha and clint.

Make both users secondary members of the web_devs group.

Configure the system so that natasha's password must be changed every 45 days, and she receives a warning 5 days before it expires.

Task 3: The Collaborative Trap (Permissions)
The developers need to work together in the new storage volume.

Change the group ownership of /srv/web_content to the web_devs group.

Ensure that any new files created inside /srv/web_content automatically inherit the web_devs group.

Set permissions so that the owner and group have full read/write/execute access, but others have zero access.

The Specifics: Create a file inside /srv/web_content owned by root. Use an Access Control List (ACL) to grant the user clint read-only access to this specific file without changing its standard ownership.

Task 4: The Network Storage (Autofs)
Your server needs to connect to an older legacy NFS server, but only when requested.

Configure autofs so that when a user accesses /net/public, it automatically mounts an NFS share.

Simulation constraint: Since you don't have a real NFS server, configure the autofs map to mount a local directory. Map /net/public to mount your own /var/ftp directory using the -bind option.

Task 5: The Silent Web Server (SELinux & Firewalld)
You need to host an internal status page, but security dictates it cannot use standard ports.

Install httpd and enable it to start on boot.

Change the Apache configuration so it listens on port 8090.

Create a simple index.html file in the default /var/www/html directory.

Configure SELinux to allow httpd to bind to port 8090.

Configure the firewall to permanently allow traffic on port 8090.

Task 6: The "Advanced" Boolean
The web developers have written a script that requires the Apache web server to connect to an external database.

By default, SELinux prevents httpd from initiating outbound network connections.

Find the correct SELinux boolean that allows the web server to connect to the network/database, and turn it ON persistently.

Task 7: The Rootless Container (The Heavy Hitter)
Natasha needs to run a lightweight proxy container that survives system reboots.

Log in as the user natasha.

Pull the nginx image from a public registry.

Run the container named natasha_proxy in the background.

Map port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container.

The Trap: Map the directory /srv/web_content (from Task 1) to /usr/share/nginx/html inside the container. You must handle the SELinux context correctly for this volume map, or the container will get a Permission Denied error.

Configure the container to start automatically as a systemd user service for natasha.

Ensure the service starts even if natasha is not currently logged into the server.

Task 8: The Automation Backup
Create a cron job for the root user that runs every day at 11:30 PM.

The job must execute the following command: tar -czvf /root/web_backup.tar.gz /srv/web_content.

The Strategy Check
Look at the structure of this exam. If you mess up Task 1 (/srv/web_content), you automatically fail Task 3 (Permissions), Task 7 (Containers), and Task 8 (Backups) because they all rely on that specific mount point existing and being persistent. That is 40% of the exam wiped out by one bad /etc/fstab entry.

Set your timer for 2.5 hours. Fire up the RHEL 9 VM.

